    <section id="warnings">
      <h2>Warnings</h2>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Meaning Can Become a Source of Grandiosity">
        The search for meaning can sometimes produce a problematic inflation of self-importance — the sense that your work must have world-historical significance to be truly meaningful. But research on meaning consistently shows that meaning is found at every scale of contribution, from raising children well to maintaining a beautiful garden to serving customers with genuine care. The requirement that meaning be grand is itself an obstacle to finding it in the rich texture of ordinary life.
      </ContentBox>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Meaning Can Be Used to Rationalize Overwork">
        "I find my work deeply meaningful" is sometimes a genuine expression of eudaimonic engagement and sometimes a rationalization for working in ways that damage health, relationships, and other sources of meaning. Meaningful work is not a license to neglect every other dimension of a flourishing life. The research on eudaimonic well-being consistently identifies multiple domains — relationships, personal growth, health, contribution — as components of flourishing. Sacrificing all of them for one is not eudaimonia; it is a narrowed life with a compelling narrative.
      </ContentBox>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Pleasure Is Not the Enemy">
        The argument for prioritizing meaning over pleasure should not be read as a brief for asceticism or the suppression of enjoyment. Epicurus himself was not a hedonist in the popular sense — he advocated for simple, sustainable pleasures (friendship, good food, philosophical conversation) over intense, short-lived ones. The point is not to eliminate pleasure but to ensure that your life is not organized primarily around its pursuit — because a life organized primarily around pleasure tends to produce both less pleasure and less meaning than a life organized around meaning that includes pleasure as a companion.
      </ContentBox>
    </section>

